for a single task

74
00:04:35,550 --> 00:04:38,194
rather than serving as a general
foundation for multiple

75
00:04:38,254 --> 00:04:44,072
applications. Section. Generally,
foundation models use a two-stage training

76
00:04:44,112 --> 00:04:46,774
process. First, they go through what we
call a

77
00:04:46,913 --> 00:04:50,016
pre-training, and then second, they can be
adapted through

78
00:04:50,055 --> 00:04:54,358
various mechanisms, like fine-tuning or
scaffolding, to perform specific

79
00:04:54,399 --> 00:04:57,961
tasks. Rather than learning from human
labeled examples for

80
00:04:58,021 --> 00:05:01,584
specific tasks, these models learn by
finding patterns in

81
00:05:01,744 --> 00:05:05,812
huge amounts of unlabeled data. There is
figure 1.24

82
00:05:06,252 --> 00:05:09,413
in the textbook here. It depicts on the
opportunities

83
00:05:09,533 --> 00:05:13,214
and risks of foundation models. Pre-
training is the initial

84
00:05:13,254 --> 00:05:16,295
phase, where the model learns general
patterns and knowledge

85
00:05:16,355 --> 00:05:19,276
from massive data sets of millions or
billions of

86
00:05:19,317 --> 00:05:22,937
examples. During this phase, the model
isn't trained for

87
00:05:23,017 --> 00:05:26,980
any specific task. Instead, it develops
broad capabilities that

88
00:05:27,019 --> 00:05:31,021
can later be specialized. This generality
is both powerful

89
00:05:31,300 --> 00:05:34,764
and concerning from a safety perspective.
While it enables

90
00:05:34,824 --> 00:05:37,548
the model to adapt to many different
tasks, it

91
00:05:37,649 --> 00:05:40,675
also means we can't easily predict or
constrain what

92
00:05:40,714 --> 00:05:43,675
the model might learn to do. The textbook
includes

93
00:05:43,774 --> 00:05:48,175
figure 1.25 here. It depicts on the
opportunities and

94
00:05:48,255 --> 00:05:52,677
risks of foundation models. Self-
supervised learning is the key

95
00:05:52,757 --> 00:05:56,560
technical innovation that makes foundation
models possible. This is

96
00:05:56,620 --> 00:06:00,360
how we actually implement the pre-training
phase. Unlike traditional

97
00:06:00,420 --> 00:06:04,682
supervised learning, which requires human
labeled data, SSL leverages

98
00:06:04,742 --> 00:06:07,223
the inherent structure of the data itself
to create

99
00:06:07,244 --> 00:06:11,380
training signals. For example, instead of
manually labeling images,

100
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:13,581
we might just hide part of a full image

101
00:06:13,620 --> 00:06:15,721
we already have and ask a model to predict

102
00:06:15,762 --> 00:06:17,762
what the rest should be. So it might
predict

103
00:06:17,802 --> 00:06:19,463
the bottom half of an image given the top

104
00:06:19,502 --> 00:06:22,923
half, learning about which objects often
appear together. As

105
00:06:22,963 --> 00:06:25,605
an example, it might learn that images
with trees

106
00:06:25,685 --> 00:06:28,086
and grass at the top often have more grass

107
00:06:28,305 --> 00:06:30,766
or maybe a path at the bottom. It learns

108
00:06:30,826 --> 00:06:33,747
about objects and their context. Trees and
grass often

109
00:06:33,766 --> 00:06:36,067
appear in parks. Dogs are often found in
these

110
00:06:36,108 --> 00:06:39,968
environments. paths are usually horizontal
and so on. These

111
00:06:40,028 --> 00:06:42,548
learned representations can then be used
for a wide

112
00:06:42,588 --> 00:06:45,310
variety of tasks that the model was not
explicitly

113
00:06:45,350 --> 00:06:48,949
trained for, like identifying dogs and
images, or recognizing

114
00:06:48,990 --> 00:06:53,011
parks, all without any human-provided
labels. The same concept

115
00:06:53,050 --> 00:06:55,411
applies in language. A model might predict
the next

116
00:06:55,451 --> 00:06:57,632
word in a sentence, such as the cat sat

117
00:06:57,752 --> 00:07:01,213
on the learning grammar, syntax, and
context, as long

118
00:07:01,252 --> 00:07:03,413
as we repeat this over huge amounts of
text.

119
00:07:04,117 --> 00:07:07,740
After pre-training, foundation models can
be adapted through two

120
00:07:07,819 --> 00:07:13,684
main approaches, fine-tuning and in-
context prompting. Fine-tuning involves
additional

121
00:07:13,744 --> 00:07:16,346
training on a specific task or data set to

122
00:07:16,406 --> 00:07:20,048
specialize the model's capabilities. For
example, we might use

123
00:07:20,148 --> 00:07:24,211
reinforcement learning from human
feedback, RHLF, to make language

124
00:07:24,250 --> 00:07:27,293
models better at following instructions or
being more helpful.

125
00:07:27,992 --> 00:07:30,814
Prompting, on the other hand, involves
providing the model

126
00:07:30,875 --> 00:07:33,855
with carefully crafted inputs that guide
it toward desired

127
00:07:33,896 --> 00:07:37,959
behaviors without additional training. The
training process of foundation

128
00:07:37,999 --> 00:07:42,922
models creates several unique safety
challenges. First, the self-supervised

129
00:07:42,982 --> 00:07:45,963
nature of pre-training means we have
limited control over

130
00:07:46,002 --> 00:07:49,245
what the model learns. It might develop
unintended capabilities

131
00:07:49,324 --> 00:07:53,569
or behaviors. Second, the adaptation
process needs to reliably

132
00:07:53,629 --> 00:07:58,012
preserve any safety properties we've
established during pre-training. Finally,

133
00:07:58,211 --> 00:08:00,954
the massive scale of training data and
compute makes

134
00:08:01,014 --> 00:08:03,737
it difficult to thoroughly understand or
audit what the

135
00:08:03,757 --> 00:08:06,718
model has learned. Many of the safety
challenges we'll

136
00:08:06,759 --> 00:08:10,583
discuss throughout this book from goal
misgeneralization to scalable

137
00:08:10,663 --> 00:08:13,545
oversight are deeply connected to how
these models are

138
00:08:13,584 --> 00:08:19,093
trained and adapted. Section Properties
The ability of foundation

139
00:08:19,132 --> 00:08:23,416
models to transfer knowledge, generalize
across many different domains,

140
00:08:23,976 --> 00:08:27,880
and develop emergent capabilities means we
can't rely on

141
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:33,065
traditional safety approaches that assume
narrow, predictable behavior. Transfer

142
00:08:33,105 --> 00:08:35,947
learning is the ability to transfer
