143
00:08:36,008 --> 00:08:39,831
pre-training to new tasks and domains.
Rather than starting

144
00:08:39,850 --> 00:08:42,453
from scratch for each task, we can
leverage the

145
00:08:42,533 --> 00:08:46,076
general knowledge these models have
already acquired. This property

146
00:08:46,157 --> 00:08:49,658
enables rapid adaptation and deployment.
It also means that

147
00:08:49,719 --> 00:08:53,201
both capabilities and safety risks can
transfer in unexpected

148
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:56,582
ways. For example, a model might transfer
not just

149
00:08:56,724 --> 00:09:00,745
useful knowledge, but also harmful biases
or undesired behaviors

150
00:09:00,826 --> 00:09:04,557
to new applications. Zero-shot and few-
shot learning is the

151
00:09:04,618 --> 00:09:07,799
ability to perform new tasks with very few
examples,

152
00:09:08,260 --> 00:09:12,082
or even no examples at all. For example,
GPT-4

153
00:09:12,163 --> 00:09:15,184
can solve novel reasoning problems just
from a natural

154
00:09:15,225 --> 00:09:18,787
language description of the task. This
emergent ability to

155
00:09:18,846 --> 00:09:22,769
generalize to new situations is powerful,
but concerning from

156
00:09:22,808 --> 00:09:25,870
a safety perspective. If models can adapt
to novel

157
00:09:25,910 --> 00:09:29,472
situations in unexpected ways, it becomes
harder to predict

158
00:09:29,573 --> 00:09:33,755
and control their behavior and deployment.
Generalization in foundation

159
00:09:33,796 --> 00:09:37,860
models works differently from traditional
AI systems. Rather than

